To incorporate modifications to the globe's material properties and initial rotation, you can utilize callbacks provided by the `react-globe.gl` library. The `onGlobeReady` callback is particularly useful, as it gives you access to the globe instance when it's ready. You can set up the globe's rotation and material properties inside this callback.

Here's how you could modify your `GlobeComponent` to include these changes:

```jsx
import React, { useEffect, useState, useRef } from 'react';
import Globe from 'react-globe.gl';
import { useRouter } from 'next/router';
import { Color } from 'three'; // Make sure to import Color from three
// ... other imports ...

const GlobeComponent = () => {
    const [arcsData, setArcsData] = useState([]);
    const router = useRouter();
    const globeEl = useRef(); // Create a ref to access the Globe instance

    useEffect(() => {
        const handleRouteChange = () => {
            // Update state here to ensure fresh data is fetched when a route changes
            setArcsData(travelHistory.flights);
        };

        router.events.on('routeChangeComplete', handleRouteChange);

        // Fetch the initial data
        setArcsData(travelHistory.flights);

        return () => {
            router.events.off('routeChangeComplete', handleRouteChange);
        };
    }, [router.events]);

    useEffect(() => {
        if (globeEl.current) {
            const globeMaterial = globeEl.current.globeMaterial();
            globeMaterial.color = new Color(0x3a228a);
            globeMaterial.emissive = new Color(0x220038);
            globeMaterial.emissiveIntensity = 0.1;
            globeMaterial.shininess = 0.7;

            // Ensure rotation is applied after globe materials have been
            // adjusted. These are method calls, not properties to set.
            globeEl.current.rotateY(-Math.PI * (1 / 9));
            globeEl.current.rotateZ(-Math.PI / 60);
        }
    }, []);

    return (
        <Globe
            ref={globeEl}
            // ... other props ...
            onGlobeReady={() => {
                // Initial rotation along the X-axis
                globeEl.current.rotateX(-Math.PI * (1 / 50));
            }}
            // ... other props ...
        />
    );
};

export default GlobeComponent;
```

In this modified code, a `useRef` hook is used to create a reference (`globeEl`) to the globe instance, which allows direct manipulation of the globe after it is mounted. The `useEffect` hook that runs only once (because of an empty dependency array) is where you adjust the properties of the globe material and apply the rotations. The `onGlobeReady` callback property is set to handle additional rotation on the globe once it's ready.

If at any point you need to react to changes after updating the globe's properties or you need to adjust the rotation dynamically, you could include additional logic within the `useEffect` hook to respond to those changes.

To set the background color of the globe to be fully transparent, you can pass an RGBA (red, green, blue, alpha) color string with the alpha channel set to 0 to the `backgroundColor` prop of the `Globe` component. The alpha channel controls the opacity, with `0` being fully transparent and `1` being fully opaque.

Here's how you can set the background color to fully transparent in your `GlobeComponent`:

```jsx
const GlobeComponent = () => {
