In this example, we've used the RGBA string `"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0)"` which represents a fully transparent black (though the red, green, and blue values are irrelevant since alpha is 0). When you use this `backgroundColor` prop, the globe background will have no color of its own, allowing you to see through it to whatever is behind it, such as your webpage background.

Keep in mind that when setting the background to fully transparent, you may need to manage the visibility of other elements that may be behind the globe to achieve the desired design or effect on your webpage.

The `bumpImageUrl` parameter in the `react-globe.gl` library is used to set a bump map texture for the globe. A bump map is an image that creates the illusion of depth and texture on the surface of a 3D model by altering the surface normals during the rendering process. It doesn't actually change the shape of the surface, but the variations in light and shadow created by the bump map can make a surface appear as though it has a complex texture.

Here's an overview of what the `bumpImageUrl` parameter does:

- **Parameter**: `bumpImageUrl([url])`
- **Type**: Getter/setter function
- **Description**: This function can be used either to retrieve the current bump map image URL being used (getter), or to set a new bump map image URL (setter).
- **Purpose**: When you set a URL to a bump map image through this parameter, the library applies the corresponding texture to the globe's material. This texture represents the globe's terrain, making continents, mountains, and other geological features appear raised or indented on the surface of the globe, simulating a 3D effect.

When you want to use a bump map in your globe, you will provide an image URL that points to a texture that has the appropriate variations in value (light and dark areas) to represent the topography of the Earth. Typically, a bump map for the globe would be a greyscale image where white represents the highest elevation and black represents the lowest.

Here is an example of how you might set the bump map URL in your `GlobeComponent`:

```jsx
const GlobeComponent = () => {
    // ... your existing code ...

    return (
        <Globe
            // ... your other props ...
            bumpImageUrl="path/to/your/bump-map-image.jpg" // URL of your bump map image
            // ... rest of your props ...
        />
    );
};

export default GlobeComponent;
```

In this example, replace `"path/to/your/bump-map-image.jpg"` with the actual path to your bump map image. This will give the visual effect of terrain features on the globe without increasing the geometric complexity of the mesh. This can be an efficient way to add realism to the globe without using a more detailed and performance-intensive geometric mesh.

